-Ray |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=March 4, 2020 |date=March 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304220603/https://deadline.com/2020/03/the-batman-matt-reeves-batmobile-robert-pattinson-1202874256/ |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<!-- RELEASE -->\n\n<ref name=\"ReleaseDate\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-batman-june-2021-release-date-ben-affleck-not-starring-1202545821/ |title='The Batman' To Fly In Summer 2021; Ben Affleck Passes The Torch To Next Generation Of Bruce Wayne |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 31, 2019 |access-date=January 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131040637/https://deadline.com/2019/01/the-batman-june-2021-release-date-ben-affleck-not-starring-1202545821/ |archive-date=January 31, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<!-- FUTURE -->\n\n<ref name=\"DCFilmsFutureNov2019\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dc-comics-superman-michael-b-jordan-green-lantern-aquaman-birds-of-prey-1203415757/ |title=DC Films Plots Future With Superman, Green Lantern and R-Rated Movies (Exclusive) |last1=Lang |first1=Brent |last2=Kroll |first2=Justin |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 26, 2019 |access-date=November 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126172333/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dc-comics-superman-michael-b-jordan-green-lantern-aquaman-birds-of-prey-1203415757/ |archive-date=November 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1877830|The Batman}}\n\n{{Batman in popular media}}\n{{Catwoman}}\n{{DC Comics films}}\n{{DC Extended Universe}}\n{{Matt Reeves}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|Speculative fiction}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batman (film), The}}\n[[Category:2020s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2020s superhero films]]\n[[Category:2020s vigilante films]]\n[[Category:2021 films]]\n[[Category:American detective films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American superhero films]]\n[[Category:American vigilante films]]\n[[Category:Batman films]]\n[[Category:DC Extended Universe films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Matt Reeves]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Giacchino]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Merseyside]]\n[[Category:Reboot films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n", "name_user": "Draco9904", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Batman_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Lockdown", "text_new": "{{short description|Emergency protocol that prevents people or information from leaving an area}}\n{{About|the emergency measure|the mass quarantine measure|Stay-at-home order|the practice of isolating prisoners|Solitary confinement|the activist tactic of attaching oneself to an object|Lock-on (protest tactic)}}\n{{other uses|Lockdown (disambiguation)}}\n\nA '''lockdown''' is an emergency protocol that usually prevents people or information from leaving an area. The protocol can usually only be initiated by someone in a position of [[authority]]. Lockdowns can also be used to protect people inside a facility or, for example, a computing system, from a threat or other external event. Of buildings, a '''drill lockdown''' usually means that doors leading outside are locked such that no person may enter or exit. A '''full lockdown''' usually means that people must stay where they are and may not enter or exit a building or rooms within said building. If people are in a hallway, they should go to the nearest safe, enclosed room.\n[[File:Zone wise lockdown in new Bhopal 2.jpg|thumb|Barricaded streets during the lockdown due to COVID-19 outbreak in [[Bhopal]], India]]\n==Types==\nProcedures for using both emergency and preventive lockdowns must be planned. [https://www.aynva.com/2020/04/how-to-make-happiest-of-your-time.html?zx=9651e9a3f9f46c60 Lockdown] should be regulated by the Government. <ref name=lockdowntype1>[https://www.campussafetymagazine.com/blogs/why-schools-need-2-types-of-lockdowns/ Why Schools Need 2 Types of Lockdowns], campussafetymagazine.com, June 14, 2012.</ref>\n \n===Preventive lockdown===\n{{anchor|Preventive}}\n{{See also|Preventive action}}\n\nA '''preventive lockdown''' is a preemptive action plan implemented to address an unusual scenario or a weakness in the system to preempt any danger to ensure the safety and security of people, organization and systems. The focus for preventive actions is to avoid dangers and risks arising from the nonconformances to the normal circumstances, but also commonly includes improvements inefficiency. \n\nPreventive lockdowns are preemptive lockdowns to mitigate risk. Most organizations plan for the emergency lockdowns but fail to plan for other situations that might quickly degrade to dangerous levels. These protocols must be based on the type of threat, and should be kept simple and short for quick learning and implementation, and flexible enough to handle several scenarios. This allows administrators more options to choose from which are easier to use in various scenarios. For example, in case of a loud scene by a parent or an unarmed petty thief being chased by the police through the school playground, this flexible procedure allows school administrators the flexibility to implement a more limited lockdown while teaching in school continues, thus eliminating the need for complete emergency lockdown, disruption, and delays in the resumption of teaching, etc. The consequences of not having procedures to implement such lockdowns are that the situation might quickly escalate where there could be a loss of human lives.<ref name=lockdowntype1/>\n\n===Emergency lockdown===\n{{see also | Emergency procedure }}\n\n'''Emergency lockdowns''' are implemented when there is an imminent threat to the lives or risk of injury to humans, for example, a school's emergency lockdown procedures must be kept short and simple to make them easier to use under real-life crisis conditions. Simple procedures can be easily taught with periodic lockdown drills instead of lengthy training.<ref name=lockdowntype1/>\n\n=== In infectious diseases ===\n[[File:Bryn_Benidorm.jpg|thumb|Police conversing with people during a lockdown in Benidorm, Spain]]\n{{Main|Stay-at-home order}}\n{{See also|Pandemic prevention#Testing and containment}}\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the term lockdown was used for actions related to mass [[quarantine]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Resnick |first1=Brian |title=Italy and China used lockdowns to slow the coronavirus. Could we? |url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2020/3/10/21171464/coronavirus-us-lockdown-travel-restriction-italy |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=VOX |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> Lockdowns can limit movements or activities in a community while allowing most organizations to function normally, or limit movements or activities such that only organizations supplying basic needs and services can function normally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slideshare.net/KevinHilRDineros/covid19-crisis-management-and-prevention-plan?fbclid=IwAR2a74JhmEJwZCHLqA11RMtm_MX_qM1LZvAL7CJB_tj4pITiMozguGjgIJE|title=COVID-19 Crisis Management and Prevention Plan|last=Dineros|first=Kevin|last2=Dipasupil|first2=Jan Paolo|date=15 March 2020|website=COVID-19 Crisis Management and Prevention Plan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Typical scenarios==\n\n=== Schools ===\nLockdown procedures vary by school district. Generally, a lockdown means that interior and exterior doors are locked, and all students and staff must remain in their location from the time the lockdown is announced. Windows are covered, and students stand at the back of the classroom or away from windows.\n\nSince the [[Columbine High School massacre|Columbine Shooting in 1999]], lockdown procedures in schools have been constantly changing. Some schools direct teachers to continue with standard procedures while remaining quiet, while some recommend an active approach against threats.<ref>{{cite web|title=School Safety Questioned After Shooting|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/school-safety-experts-disagree-lockdown-procedures-newtown-shooting/story?id=17978485|website=ABC News|language=en|date=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Prisons===\nIn its most common usage in corrections units, the term ''lockdown'' can be defined as a course of action to control the movement of inmates. Confining all prisoners, except workers, to their cells until the end of the day is an example of a \"lockdown period\" in a corrections schedule.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} However a \"full lockdown\" is used when all prisoners are locked in their cells to prevent [[prison riots]] or unrest from spreading or during an emergency.<ref>Spiegel, Sarah. \"[https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1199&context=californialawreview Prison Race Rights: An Easy Case for Segregation].\" Calif. L. Rev. 95 (2007): 2261.</ref>\n\n===Hospitals===\nIn [[United States|US]] guidelines, occasions for preventing entry into a hospital may include: [[power failure]], [[earthquake]], [[flooding]], [[fire]], [[bomb threat]], [[hostage crisis]]  and [[active shooter]].<ref name=\"cal\">[http://www.calhospitalprepare.org/sites/main/files/file-attachments/lockdown_policy_4.doc Lockdown Policy] from California Hospital Association. Retrieved December 2012</ref><ref name=\"Iroquois\">[http://www.iroquois.org/userfiles/HP%20Lockdown%20policy.doc Lockdown Policy] at Iroquois Healthcare Alliance. Retrieved December 2012</ref> Occasions for preventing both entry and exit from a hospital may include: external contamination, [[civil disturbance]] and [[child abduction|abduction of an infant or child]].<ref name=cal/><ref name=Iroquois/>\n\n===Lean manufacturing process===\nIn [[manufacturing]], the term ''lockdown event'' refers to a [[continuous improvement]] initiative in which manufacturing in  a specific area (typically a cell or specific piece of machinery) is halted in order to contain, and determine, what are the issues that are preventing the manufacture of goods from meeting the [[quality (business)|quality]] specifications. During the ''lockdown event'' a multi disciplinary team reviews the specific area [[manufacturing]] processes, tooling and machine condition, to find the root cause(s) of the problem(s). Once changes to the process, or machine repairs that may include adjustments and/or replacement are effected, a sample run is initiated and evaluated. If the results of the [[Verification and validation|validation]] are within the required specifications, the area lockdown is lifted and production is resumed. Follow up sampling is conducted subsequently to ensure continuity of the lockdown results.\n\n== Historical events ==\n{{recentism|date=March 2020}}\nIn the wake of the [[September 11 attacks]] (2001), a three-day lockdown of American [[civilian]] [[airspace]] was initiated.\n\nIn December 2005, the [[New South Wales Police Force]] (NSW Police Force) initiated a lockdown of the [[Sutherland Shire]] and other beach areas of New South Wales to contain race rioting (and retaliative strikes). {{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAn example of a campus/school lockdown was demonstrated at the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC) on January 30, 2008, when an unknown threat was made and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) issued a lockdown on one of the buildings on campus for six hours, cordoning off the area, and a campus alert was sent via email to everyone affiliated with UBC while students and faculties were to remain locked in the building.<ref>[https://www.straight.com/article-131020/cause-for-ubc-lockdown-still-uncertain-but-initial-posting-may-reveal-some-clues Cause for UBC Lockdown still uncertain but initial posting may reveal some clues]</ref><ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/police-increase-presence-at-ubc-following-lockdown-1.741366 \"Police increase presence at UBC following lockdown\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20080131.wubclockdown0131/BNStory/National/home \"Threat prompts lockdown at UBC\"]</ref>\n\nOn April 10, 2008, two Canadian [[secondary school]]s were locked down due to suspected firearm threats. [[George S. Henry Academy]] was locked down in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] at approximately 2:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref>[http://www.insidetoronto.ca/News/NorthYork/article/45610 \"NORTH YORK: Two charged after George S. Henry Academy lockdown\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The [[Emergency Task Force (TPS)]] were contacted and the lockdown lasted for more than two hours. [[New Westminster Secondary School]] was locked down in [[New Westminster]], [[British Columbia]] at approximately 1:40&nbsp;p.m.<ref>[http://www.canada.com/theprovince/news/story.html?id=31b5f3d2-7491-4e18-8766-0c4f974ee44d&k=18879 \"Teen arrested in connection with school lockdown\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217010311/http://www2.canada.com/theprovince/news/story.html?id=31b5f3d2-7491-4e18-8766-0c4f974ee44d&k=18879 |date=2009-02-17 }}</ref> The [[Emergency Response Team]] (ERT) were called and the school was under lockdown until 4:30&nbsp;p.m. Due to the size of the school some students were not able to leave until 7:00&nbsp;p.m.\n\nOn 19 April 2013, the entire city of [[Boston]] was locked down and all public transportation stopped during the manhunt for terrorist Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, the suspects of the [[Boston Marathon bombing]], while the town of [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] was under heavy-armed police and SWAT surveillance, as well as systematic house-to-house searches.<ref>[http://www.theatlanticwire.com/national/2013/04/boston-lockdown-residents-are-asked-shelter-place-while-cops-sweep-watertown/64383/ This Is What It Looks Like When the Police Shut Down a City], ''The Atlantic Wire'', 19 Apr  2013. Retrieved Jun 2013.</ref><ref>[http://nation.time.com/2013/04/19/a-town-under-seige-watertown-residents-describe-life-under-lockdown/ A Town Under Siege: Watertown Residents Describe Life Under Lockdown], ''Time'', 19 Apr 2013. Retrieved Jun 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/apr/19/boston-lockdown-police-hunt-bombing-suspect Boston faces lockdown as police hunt for marathon bombing suspect], [[The Guardian]], 19 April 2013. Retrieved 19 April 2013.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 Brussels lockdown]], the city was locked down for days while security services sought suspects involved with the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]]. Later in 2015, a terror threat caused the [[2015 Los Angeles Unified School District closure]].\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], numerous governments responded to the disease with lockdowns of international borders and public spaces, including but not limited to [[China]], [[Colombia]], [[France]], [[Italy]], [[India]], [[Malaysia]], [[United Kingdom]], [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henley|first=Jon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/coronavirus-spain-takes-over-private-healthcare-amid-more-european-lockdowns|title=Coronavirus: France imposes lockdown as EU calls for 30-day travel ban|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-17|last2=Madrid|first2=Kim Willsher Ashifa Kassam in|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-new-york-and-la-on-lockdown-as-world-reacts-to-spread-of-covid-19-11958145|title=Coronavirus: US cities put into lockdown as COVID-19 cases worldwide overtake China|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/16/816080263/reporters-notebook-rome-under-coronavirus-lockdown|title=Reporter's Notebook: What Life Is Like In Rome Under Coronavirus Lockdown|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsworld24.in/2020/03/india-under-21-days-lockdown-to-fight-against-coronavirus.html|title=India under 21 days lockdown due to coronavirus pandemic|website=News World24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{wiktionary|lockdown}}\n* {{annotated link|Amber alert}}\n* {{annotated link|Code Adam}}\n* {{annotated link|Curfew}}\n* {{annotated link|Janata Curfew}}\n* {{annotated link|Martial law}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Criminology]]\n[[Category:Penal imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Emergency management]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Emergency protocol that prevents people or information from leaving an area}}\n{{About|the emergency measure|the mass quarantine measure|Stay-at-home order|the practice of isolating prisoners|Solitary confinement|the activist tactic of attaching oneself to an object|Lock-on (protest tactic)}}\n{{other uses|Lockdown (disambiguation)}}\n\nA '''lockdown''' is an emergency protocol that usually prevents people or information from leaving an area. The protocol can usually only be initiated by someone in a position of [[authority]]. Lockdowns can also be used to protect people inside a facility or, for example, a computing system, from a threat or other external event. Of buildings, a '''drill lockdown''' usually means that doors leading outside are locked such that no person may enter or exit. A '''full lockdown''' usually means that people must stay where they are and may not enter or exit a building or rooms within said building. If people are in a hallway, they should go to the nearest safe, enclosed room.\n[[File:Zone wise lockdown in new Bhopal 2.jpg|thumb|Barricaded streets during the lockdown due to COVID-19 outbreak in [[Bhopal]], India]]\n==Types==\nProcedures for using both emergency and preventive lockdowns must be planned.<ref name=lockdowntype1>[https://www.campussafetymagazine.com/blogs/why-schools-need-2-types-of-lockdowns/ Why Schools Need 2 Types of Lockdowns], campussafetymagazine.com, June 14, 2012.</ref>\n \n===Preventive lockdown===\n{{anchor|Preventive}}\n{{See also|Preventive action}}\n\nA '''preventive lockdown''' is a preemptive action plan implemented to address an unusual scenario or a weakness in system to preempt any danger to ensure the safety and security of people, organisation and system. The focus for preventive actions is to avoid dangers and risks arising from the nonconformances to the normal circumstances, but also commonly includes improvements in efficiency. \n\nPreventive lockdowns are preemptive lockdowns to mitigate risk. Most organisations plan for the emergency lockdowns but fail to plan for other situations which might quickly degrade to dangerous levels. These protocols must be based on the type of threat, and should be kept simple and short for quick learning and implementation, and flexible enough to handle several scenarios. This allows administrators more options to choose from which are easier to use in various scenarios. For example, in case of a loud scene by a parent or an unarmed petty thief being chased by the police through the school playground, this flexible procedure allows school administrators the flexibility to implement a more limited lockdown while teaching in school continues, this eliminating need for complete emergency lockdown, disruption and delays in resumption of teaching, etc. The consequences of not having procedures to implement such lockdowns is that the situation might quickly escalate where there could be loss of human lives.<ref name=lockdowntype1/>\n\n===Emergency lockdown===\n{{see also | Emergency procedure }}\n\n'''Emergency lockdowns''' are implemented when there is imminent threat to the lives or risk of injury to humans, for example, a school's emergency lockdown procedures must be kept short and simple to make them easier to use under real life crisis conditions. Simple procedures can be easily taught with periodic lockdown drills instead of lengthy training.<ref name=lockdowntype1/>\n\n=== In infectious diseases ===\n[[File:Bryn_Benidorm.jpg|thumb|Police conversing with people during a lockdown in Benidorm, Spain]]\n{{Main|Stay-at-home order}}\n{{See also|Pandemic prevention#Testing and containment}}\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], the term lockdown was used for actions related to mass [[quarantine]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Resnick |first1=Brian |title=Italy and China used lockdowns to slow the coronavirus. Could we? |url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2020/3/10/21171464/coronavirus-us-lockdown-travel-restriction-italy |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=VOX |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> Lockdowns can limit movements or activities in a community while allowing most organizations to function normally, or limit movements or activities such that only organizations supplying basic needs and services can function normally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slideshare.net/KevinHilRDineros/covid19-crisis-management-and-prevention-plan?fbclid=IwAR2a74JhmEJwZCHLqA11RMtm_MX_qM1LZvAL7CJB_tj4pITiMozguGjgIJE|title=COVID-19 Crisis Management and Prevention Plan|last=Dineros|first=Kevin|last2=Dipasupil|first2=Jan Paolo|date=15 March 2020|website=COVID-19 Crisis Management and Prevention Plan|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Typical scenarios==\n\n=== Schools ===\nLockdown procedures vary by school district. Generally, a lockdown means that interior and exterior doors are locked, and all students and staff must remain in their location from the time the lockdown is announced. Windows are covered, and students stand at the back of the classroom or away from windows.\n\nSince the [[Columbine High School massacre|Columbine Shooting in 1999]], lockdown procedures in schools have been constantly changing. Some schools direct teachers to continue with standard procedures while remaining quiet, while some recommend an active approach against threats.<ref>{{cite web|title=School Safety Questioned After Shooting|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/school-safety-experts-disagree-lockdown-procedures-newtown-shooting/story?id=17978485|website=ABC News|language=en|date=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Prisons===\nIn its most common usage in corrections units, the term ''lockdown'' can be defined as a course of action to control the movement of inmates. Confining all prisoners, except workers, to their cells until the end of the day is an example of a \"lockdown period\" in a corrections schedule.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} However a \"full lockdown\" is used when all prisoners are locked in their cells to prevent [[prison riots]] or unrest from spreading or during an emergency.<ref>Spiegel, Sarah. \"[https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1199&context=californialawreview Prison Race Rights: An Easy Case for Segregation].\" Calif. L. Rev. 95 (2007): 2261.</ref>\n\n===Hospitals===\nIn [[United States|US]] guidelines, occasions for preventing entry into a hospital may include: [[power failure]], [[earthquake]], [[flooding]], [[fire]], [[bomb threat]], [[hostage crisis]]  and [[active shooter]].<ref name=\"cal\">[http://www.calhospitalprepare.org/sites/main/files/file-attachments/lockdown_policy_4.doc Lockdown Policy] from California Hospital Association. Retrieved December 2012</ref><ref name=\"Iroquois\">[http://www.iroquois.org/userfiles/HP%20Lockdown%20policy.doc Lockdown Policy] at Iroquois Healthcare Alliance. Retrieved December 2012</ref> Occasions for preventing both entry and exit from a hospital may include: external contamination, [[civil disturbance]] and [[child abduction|abduction of an infant or child]].<ref name=cal/><ref name=Iroquois/>\n\n===Lean manufacturing process===\nIn [[manufacturing]], the term ''lockdown event'' refers to a [[continuous improvement]] initiative in which manufacturing in  a specific area (typically a cell or specific piece of machinery) is halted in order to contain, and determine, what are the issues that are preventing the manufacture of goods from meeting the [[quality (business)|quality]] specifications. During the ''lockdown event'' a multi disciplinary team reviews the specific area [[manufacturing]] processes, tooling and machine condition, to find the root cause(s) of the problem(s). Once changes to the process, or machine repairs that may include adjustments and/or replacement are effected, a sample run is initiated and evaluated. If the results of the [[Verification and validation|validation]] are within the required specifications, the area lockdown is lifted and production is resumed. Follow up sampling is conducted subsequently to ensure continuity of the lockdown results.\n\n== Historical events ==\n{{recentism|date=March 2020}}\nIn the wake of the [[September 11 attacks]] (2001), a three-day lockdown of American [[civilian]] [[airspace]] was initiated.\n\nIn December 2005, the [[New South Wales Police Force]] (NSW Police Force) initiated a lockdown of the [[Sutherland Shire]] and other beach areas of New South Wales to contain race rioting (and retaliative strikes). {{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAn example of a campus/school lockdown was demonstrated at the [[University of British Columbia]] (UBC) on January 30, 2008, when an unknown threat was made and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) issued a lockdown on one of the buildings on campus for six hours, cordoning off the area, and a campus alert was sent via email to everyone affiliated with UBC while students and faculties were to remain locked in the building.<ref>[https://www.straight.com/article-131020/cause-for-ubc-lockdown-still-uncertain-but-initial-posting-may-reveal-some-clues Cause for UBC Lockdown still uncertain but initial posting may reveal some clues]</ref><ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/police-increase-presence-at-ubc-following-lockdown-1.741366 \"Police increase presence at UBC following lockdown\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20080131.wubclockdown0131/BNStory/National/home \"Threat prompts lockdown at UBC\"]</ref>\n\nOn April 10, 2008, two Canadian [[secondary school]]s were locked down due to suspected firearm threats. [[George S. Henry Academy]] was locked down in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] at approximately 2:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref>[http://www.insidetoronto.ca/News/NorthYork/article/45610 \"NORTH YORK: Two charged after George S. Henry Academy lockdown\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The [[Emergency Task Force (TPS)]] were contacted and the lockdown lasted for more than two hours. [[New Westminster Secondary School]] was locked down in [[New Westminster]], [[British Columbia]] at approximately 1:40&nbsp;p.m.<ref>[http://www.canada.com/theprovince/news/story.html?id=31b5f3d2-7491-4e18-8766-0c4f974ee44d&k=18879 \"Teen arrested in connection with school lockdown\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217010311/http://www2.canada.com/theprovince/news/story.html?id=31b5f3d2-7491-4e18-8766-0c4f974ee44d&k=18879 |date=2009-02-17 }}</ref> The [[Emergency Response Team]] (ERT) were called and the school was under lockdown until 4:30&nbsp;p.m. Due to the size of the school some students were not able to leave until 7:00&nbsp;p.m.\n\nOn 19 April 2013, the entire city of [[Boston]] was locked down and all public transportation stopped during the manhunt for terrorist Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, the suspects of the [[Boston Marathon bombing]], while the town of [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] was under heavy-armed police and SWAT surveillance, as well as systematic house-to-house searches.<ref>[http://www.theatlanticwire.com/national/2013/04/boston-lockdown-residents-are-asked-shelter-place-while-cops-sweep-watertown/64383/ This Is What It Looks Like When the Police Shut Down a City], ''The Atlantic Wire'', 19 Apr  2013. Retrieved Jun 2013.</ref><ref>[http://nation.time.com/2013/04/19/a-town-under-seige-watertown-residents-describe-life-under-lockdown/ A Town Under Siege: Watertown Residents Describe Life Under Lockdown], ''Time'', 19 Apr 2013. Retrieved Jun 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/apr/19/boston-lockdown-police-hunt-bombing-suspect Boston faces lockdown as police hunt for marathon bombing suspect], [[The Guardian]], 19 April 2013. Retrieved 19 April 2013.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2015 Brussels lockdown]], the city was locked down for days while security services sought suspects involved with the [[November 2015 Paris attacks]]. Later in 2015, a terror threat caused the [[2015 Los Angeles Unified School District closure]].\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], numerous governments responded to the disease with lockdowns of international borders and public spaces, including but not limited to [[China]], [[Colombia]], [[France]], [[Italy]], [[India]], [[Malaysia]], [[United Kingdom]], [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Henley|first=Jon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/coronavirus-spain-takes-over-private-healthcare-amid-more-european-lockdowns|title=Coronavirus: France imposes lockdown as EU calls for 30-day travel ban|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-17|last2=Madrid|first2=Kim Willsher Ashifa Kassam in|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-new-york-and-la-on-lockdown-as-world-reacts-to-spread-of-covid-19-11958145|title=Coronavirus: US cities put into lockdown as COVID-19 cases worldwide overtake China|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/16/816080263/reporters-notebook-rome-under-coronavirus-lockdown|title=Reporter's Notebook: What Life Is Like In Rome Under Coronavirus Lockdown|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsworld24.in/2020/03/india-under-21-days-lockdown-to-fight-against-coronavirus.html|title=India under 21 days lockdown due to coronavirus pandemic|website=News World24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{wiktionary|lockdown}}\n* {{annotated link|Amber alert}}\n* {{annotated link|Code Adam}}\n* {{annotated link|Curfew}}\n* {{annotated link|Janata Curfew}}\n* {{annotated link|Martial law}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Criminology]]\n[[Category:Penal imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Emergency management]]\n", "name_user": "Niiryaa", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eTypes)", "url_page": "//en.wiki