style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n|- \n! rowspan=2| [[1985 James Hardie 1000|1985]]\n|align=\"left\" rowspan=2| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Dick Johnson Racing|Palmer Tube Mills]]\n|align=\"left\" rowspan=2| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Dick Johnson (racing driver)|Dick Johnson]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Third-generation Ford Mustang#1983\u20131986|Ford Mustang GT]]\n| A\n| 159\n| 7th\n| 7th\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| [[Third-generation Ford Mustang#1983\u20131986|Ford Mustang GT]]\n| A\n| -\n| DNS\n| DNS\n|- \n! [[1986 James Hardie 1000|1986]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Enzed Team Perkins]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[David \"Skippy\" Parsons|David Parsons]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| C\n| 140\n| 25th\n| 18th\n|- \n! [[1987 James Hardie 1000|1987]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Enzed Team Perkins]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Denny Hulme]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| 1\n| 2\n| DNF\n| DNF\n|- \n! [[1988 Tooheys 1000|1988]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Holden Special Vehicles]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Denny Hulme]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Tom Walkinshaw]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A SV]]\n| A\n| 137\n| DNF\n| DNF\n|- \n! [[1989 Tooheys 1000|1989]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Holden Racing Team]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Tomas Mezera]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A SV]]\n| A\n| 158\n| 6th\n| 6th\n|- \n! [[1990 Tooheys 1000|1990]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Tomas Mezera]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A SV]]\n| 1\n| 161\n| style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\" | '''3rd'''\n| style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\" | '''3rd'''\n|- \n! [[1991 Tooheys 1000|1991]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Mobil 1 Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Tomas Mezera]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VN Commodore SS Group A SV]]\n| 1\n| 65\n| DNF\n| DNF\n|- \n! [[1992 Tooheys 1000|1992]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Steve Harrington (racing driver)|Steve Harrington]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VL Commodore SS Group A SV]]\n| A\n| 135\n| 9th\n| 8th\n|- \n! [[1993 Tooheys 1000|1993]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gregg Hansford]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VP Commodore]]\n| A\n| 161\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n|- \n! [[1994 Tooheys 1000|1994]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gregg Hansford]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VP Commodore]]\n| A\n| 161\n| style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\" | '''3rd'''\n| style=\"background:#ffdf9f;\" | '''3rd'''\n|- \n! [[1995 Tooheys 1000|1995]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Ingall]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VR Commodore]]\n| A\n| 161\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n|- \n! [[1996 AMP Bathurst 1000|1996]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Ingall]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VP Commodore]]\n| \n| 160\n| 6th\n| 6th\n|- \n! [[1997 Primus 1000 Classic|1997]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Ingall]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VS Commodore]]\n| L1\n| 161\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n|- \n! [[1998 FAI 1000|1998]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Ingall]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VT Commodore]]\n| OC\n| 161\n| style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| '''2nd'''\n| style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"| '''2nd'''\n|- \n! [[1999 FAI 1000|1999]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Ingall]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VT Commodore]]\n| \n| 161\n| 7th\n| 7th\n|- \n! [[2000 FAI 1000|2000]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Ingall]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VT Commodore]]\n| \n| 159\n| 11th\n| 11th\n|- \n! [[2001 V8 Supercar 1000|2001]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Russell Ingall]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VX Commodore]]\n| \n| 161\n| 8th\n| 8th\n|- \n! [[2002 Bob Jane T-Marts 1000|2002]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Paul Dumbrell]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VX Commodore]]\n| \n| 161\n| 5th\n| 5th\n|- \n! [[2003 Bob Jane T-Marts 1000|2003]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perkins Engineering|Castrol Perkins Racing]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Steven Richards]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Holden VY Commodore]]\n| \n| 161\n| 4th\n| 4th\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://f1rejects.com/drivers/perkins/ Larry Perkins] Comprehensive Biography and Race Record\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{succession box|before=None|title=[[FIA European Formula 3 Championship (established in 1975)|European Formula Three Champion]]|years=1975|after=[[Riccardo Patrese]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Dick Johnson (race driver)|Dick Johnson]]<br>[[John French (racing driver)|John French]] | title = Winner of the [[Bathurst 1000]] | years = [[1982 James Hardie 1000|1982]], [[1983 James Hardie 1000|1983]], [[1984 James Hardie 1000|1984]]<br>(with [[Peter Brock]] and [[John Harvey (motorsport)|John Harvey]] ([[1983 James Hardie 1000|1983]])) | after = [[John Goss (race driver)|John Goss]]<br>[[Armin Hahne]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Jim Richards (race driver)|Jim Richards]]<br>[[Mark Skaife]] | title = Winner of the [[Bathurst 1000]] | years = [[1993 Tooheys 1000|1993]]<br>(with [[Gregg Hansford]]) | after = [[Dick Johnson (race driver)|Dick Johnson]]<br>[[John Bowe (racing driver)|John Bowe]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Dick Johnson (race driver)|Dick Johnson]]<br>[[John Bowe (racing driver)|John Bowe]] | title = Winner of the [[Bathurst 1000]] | years = [[1995 Tooheys 1000|1995]]<br>(with [[Russell Ingall]]) | after = [[Craig Lowndes]]<br>[[Greg Murphy]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Craig Lowndes]]<br>[[Greg Murphy]] | title = Winner of the [[Bathurst 1000|Bathurst Classic]] | years = [[1997 Primus 1000 Classic|1997]]<br>(with [[Russell Ingall]]) | after = [[Jason Bright]]<br>[[Steven Richards]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Bathurst 1000 winners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perkins, Larry}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:Amon Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Australian Formula 2 drivers]]\n[[Category:Australian Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Australian racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Australian Touring Car Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:Bathurst 1000 winners]]\n[[Category:Brabham Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:BRM Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Boro Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:FIA European Formula 3 Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula Ford drivers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Surtees Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Supercars Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:World Sportscar Championship drivers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American politician|Larry L. Perkins}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Larry Perkins\n| image             =\n| caption           = \n| nationality       = {{flagicon|AUS}} Australian\n| birth_name        = Larry Clifton Perkins\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1950|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Murrayville, Victoria|Murrayville]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| retired           = 2003\n| related to        = [[Jack Perkins (racing driver)|Jack Perkins]] (son)\n| last series       = [[Australian Touring Car Championship|ATCC]] / [[V8 Supercar]]\n| years active      = 1981, 1985\u20132003\n| teams             = [[Holden Dealer Team]]<br>[[Perkins Engineering]]\n| starts            = 160\n| wins              = 4\n| poles             = \n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = 4th\n| year              = [[1994 Australian Touring Car Championship|1994]], [[1995 Australian Touring Car Championship|1995]] & [[1998 Australian Touring Car Championship]]\n| prev series       = <!-- previous series with line breaks -->\n| prev series years = \n| titles            = [[FIA European Formula 3 Championship (established in 1975)|European Formula Three Championship]]<br>[[Rothmans International Series|Australian Formula 5000 Championship]]<br>[[1979 Australian Rallycross Championship|Australian Rallycross Championship]]\n| title years       = 1975<br><br>1979<br><br>1979\n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n| module            =\n{{Infobox F1 driver|embed=yes\n| Years = {{F1|1974}}, {{F1|1976}} \u2013 {{F1|1977}}\n| Team(s) = [[Amon (Formula One team)|Amon]], [[Boro (Formula One)|Boro]], [[Brabham]], [[British Racing Motors|BRM]], [[Surtees]]\n| name = \n| Races = 15 (11 starts)\n| Championships = 0\n| Wins = 0\n| Podiums = 0\n| Points = 0\n| Poles = 0\n| Fastest laps = 0\n| First race = [[1974 German Grand Prix]] (DNQ) / [[1976 Spanish Grand Prix]] (13th)\n| First win = \n| Last win = \n| Last race = [[1977 Belgian Grand Prix]] (12th) / [[1977 French Grand Prix]] (DNQ)\n}}\n}}\n[[File:Cowangie - Hometown of Larry Perkins.jpg|thumb|Sign proclaiming [[Cowangie, Victoria|Cowangie]] to be the \"Hometown of Larry Perkins\"]]\n[[File:Brock-vk.jpg|thumb|right|The [[1984 Bathurst 1000]] winning Holden Commodore]]\n\n'''Larry Clifton Perkins''' (born 18 March 1950 in [[Murrayville, Victoria|Murrayville]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/drv-perlar.html |title=Drivers:Larry Perkins |publisher=grandprix.com |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> is a former [[racing driver]] and [[V8 Supercar]] team owner from [[Australia]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early years===\nGrowing up on a farm in [[Cowangie, Victoria|Cowangie]] in the [[Mallee (Victoria)|Mallee]] region of Victoria, Larry, the son of racing driver Eddie Perkins who had won the 1956 RedeX [[Round Australia Trial]], developed a love for cars from a young age and loved tinkering with the farm machinery. In 1970 he was recruited as a mechanic/driver for [[Harry Firth]]'s [[Holden Dealer Team]], and although he didn't do much road racing for the team, he did race in [[Rallycross]] alongside team driver [[Peter Brock]], and was also involved with the development of the stillborn [[Holden LJ Torana GTR XU-1]] [[Holden V8 engine|V8]] project which was canned in mid-1972 by the \"[[Supercar scare]]\".\n\n===Racing career===\nAfter winning the [[Australian Formula Ford Championship|TAA Formula Ford \"Driver To Europe\" Series]] in 1971 and the [[Australian Formula 2 Championship]] in 1972 (both times in an [[Elfin 600]]), Perkins travelled to Europe where he won the 1975 [[FIA European Formula 3 Championship (established in 1975)|European Formula Three Championship]]. He also raced in [[Formula One]] during the 1974, 1976 and 1977 seasons. After failing to secure a permanent drive in Formula One he returned to Australia, winning the [[Rothmans International Series]] in 1979 in an [[Elfin MR8]] for the [[Ansett Team Elfin]] factory team run by [[Elfin Sports Cars]] founder [[Garrie Cooper]], and the [[1979 Australian Rallycross Championship]] in a [[Volkswagen Beetle]].<ref>John Lemm, Perkins is Australian Champ!, Racing Car News, August 1979, page 68.</ref> During 1982 and 1983 he worked with brother Garry on the construction of [[The Quiet Achiever]] solar car. He was one of the drivers of the car during the transcontinental solar crossing of Australia, the car using only a photovoltaic solar cell source.<ref name=\"Journey\">{{cite web |url=http://www.snooksmotorsport.com.au/solartrek/Solar_Trek/Solar_Trek_The_Journey.htm |title=The Journey |publisher=Snooks Motorsport |accessdate=7 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323011759/http://www.snooksmotorsport.com.au/solartrek/Solar_Trek/Solar_Trek_The_Journey.htm |archivedate=23 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> During these years he met with success in Australian [[Touring Car racing|Touring Cars]] and in 1988 he returned to [[Europe]] to race at the [[Le Mans 24 Hour]] with [[Tom Walkinshaw Racing]], finishing 4th.\n \nAfter returning home from Europe, Perkins made his [[Bathurst 1000]] debut in 1977 in a [[Holden Torana#LX|Holden LX Torana SS A9X Hatchback]] where he finished third with [[Peter Janson]]. He went on to win the race six times (1982, 1983, 1984, 1993, 1995, 1997), with co-drivers Peter Brock (1982\u201384), [[John Harvey (racing driver)|John Harvey]] (1983) (all for the Holden Dealer Team which by then was owned by Brock with Perkins in charge of race car building and preparation), [[Gregg Hansford]] (1993) and in his last two wins in 1995 and 1997 with [[Russell Ingall]], winning each time in an Australian developed [[Holden Commodore]].\n\nArguably his most memorable win was in the [[1995 Tooheys 1000]] in which he dropped to last place after a pit stop at the end of the first lap to replace a flat tyre, and subsequently gained the lead with less than 10 laps remaining after the [[Ford EF Falcon|Ford Falcon]] of [[Glenn Seton]] retired having dropped a valve in the [[Ford Boss 302 engine|engine]]. Perkins and co-driver Russell Ingall thus became only the second driving combination in the history of the race to recover from last place to win the event. Perkins has however, never won an [[Australian Touring Car Championship]], his best championship results being three fourth places.\n\n===Formula One===\n\nPerkins made his first appearance in Formula One at the [[1974 German Grand Prix]] for [[Chris Amon Racing]]. With regular driver and team owner [[Chris Amon]] sidelined with sinustis after just one practice lap, Perkins took over in the AF101, failing to qualify after crashing on the second day of practice. \n\nIn 1976 he signed a deal with the works [[Boro (Formula One)|Boro]] team, for the team's first season. He made his first Formula One start at the [[1976 Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish Grand Prix]], finishing 13th before achieving a seasons best result of 8th at the following race in [[1976 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgium]]. He failed to qualify at [[1976 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco]] and retired from the [[1976 Swedish Grand Prix|Swedish Grand Prix]] after blowing an engine. With the team's money drying up, Perkins only made two further appearances in a Boro, retiring from the [[1976 Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch]] and [[1976 Italian Grand Prix|Italian]] Grands Prix, and after Boro's withdrawal, was left without a drive. He replaced [[Rolf Stommelen]] at [[Brabham]] for the final three races of the year, finishing in 17th position in [[1976 Canadian Grand Prix|Canada]] and retiring from the remaining two races. \n\nFor the beginning of 1977, the Australian secured a drive for Stanley BRM, the remnants of the once great [[British Racing Motors|BRM]] team. After his car failed to be delivered on time for the opening Grand Prix, he made his first appearance at the [[1977 Brazilian Grand Prix|Brazilian Grand Prix]], albeit 12.1 seconds of the pace and retiring after one lap. Lapped five times before finishing 15th in [[1977 South African Grand Prix|South Africa]], Perkins lost his seat to [[Conny Andersson (racing driver)|Conny Andersson]] at the beginning of the European season. He had a brief stint at [[Surtees]], finishing 12th in [[1977 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgium]] and failing to qualify in [[1977 Swedish Grand Prix|Sweden]]. At the [[1977 French Grand Prix|French Grand Prix]], he drove in Friday practice, but was replaced by [[Patrick Tambay]] the next day. This marked the end of Perkins' brief and unsuccessful Formula One career.\n\n===Retirement and legacy===\nPerkins retired from driving in 2003, aged 53 and was inducted into the [[V8 Supercars Hall of Fame]] in 2008. In addition to his racing credentials as a driver he is an accomplished automotive engineer and engine-builder having built many race cars for both his own team and for other racing teams. He is well known for his outgoing and humorous personality. His nickname is \"LP\", but he is often referred to as \"[[Lightning]] Larry\" or \"[[Larrikin]] Larry\". Larry is the father of V8 Supercar race winner [[Jack Perkins (racing driver)|Jack Perkins]].\n\nOn 7 December 2017, the \"'''Larry Perkins Trophy'''\" was named in his honour. It is awarded to the driver who accumulates the most points across the four races at the [[Beaurepaires Melbourne 400]], the Supercars event supporting the [[Australian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supercars.com/news/championship/supercars-to-race-for-larry-perkins-trophy-at-agp/|title=Supercars to race for Larry Perkins Trophy at AGP|publisher=Supercars|first=Mitchell|last=Adam|date=7 December 2017|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Perkins and his brother Peter discovered the lost cache of  equipment left behind in the [[Simpson Desert]] by explorers [[Henry Vere Barclay]] and Ronald MacPherson in 1904. The explorers had been forced to abandon the load, which included camel tanks, tools, scientific equipment and personal belongings, in order to cross sandhills to get to a water source. The Perkins' discovery was described as a \"highly significant archaeological find\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-07-16/racing-car-driver-larry-perkins-finds-explorers-cache-of-eqipmen/9992376 |title=Racing legend Larry Perkins swaps racetrack for outback and returns with buried treasure |first=Claire |last=Moodie |date=16 July 2018 |work=ABC News |accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Racing record==\n\n===Career summary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Season\n! Series\n! Position\n! Car\n! Entrant / Team\n|-\n! 1970\n| [[1970 Formula Ford National Series|Formula Ford National Series]]\n|align=\"center\" | 5th\n| [[Elfin 600]] [[Ford]]\n| B.S. Stillwell & Co. \n|-\n! 1971\n| [[1971 National Formula Ford Driver to Europe Series|National Formula Ford Driver to Europe Series]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n| [[Elfin 600]] [[Ford]]\n| BS Stillwell & Co Pty Ltd\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 1972\n| [[1972 Australian Drivers' Championship|Australian Drivers' Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" | 11th\n|rowspan=2| [[Elfin 600B]] [[Ford]]\n|rowspan=2| Provincial Motors\n|-\n| [[1972 Australian Formula 2 Championship|Australian Formula 2 Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 1975\n| [[FIA European Formula Three Championship|European Formula Three Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#ffffbf;\"| '''1st'''\n|rowspan=2| [[Ralt RT1]] [[Ford]]\n|rowspan=2| Team Cowangie\n|-\n| [[British Formula 3 Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" | 5th\n|-\n! 1978\n| Peter Stuyvesant International Formula Pacific Series <ref>[http://www.driverdb.com/standings/2178-1978/ Peter Stuyvesant International Formula Pacific Series 1978] Retrieved from http://www.driverdb.com on 30 January 2011</ref>\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#dfdfdf;\"|