{"title_page": "Ruth I. Michler", "text_new": "{{short description|American mathematician}}\n{{infobox scientist\n  | name        = Ruth I. Michler\n  | image       = \n  | birth_date  =  March 8, 1967\n  | birth_place = [[Ithaca, New York]]\n  | death_date = November 1, 2000\n  | nationality       = American\n  | fields            = [[commutative algebra]], [[algebraic geometry]]\n  | workplaces        = [[University of North Texas]]\n  | alma_mater  = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n  | doctoral_advisor  = [[Arthur Ogus]], [[Mariusz Wodzicki]]\n  | known_for   = \n}}\n\n'''Ruth I. Michler''' (March 8, 1967 to November 1, 2000)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Michler.html|title=Ruth Michler biography|website=www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://pi.math.cornell.edu/News/2006-2007/michler_dedication.html|title=Cornell Math - About Ruth Michler|website=pi.math.cornell.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.northeastern.edu/iarrobino/~michler/Commem|title=Commemorating Dr. Ruth Michler|website=web.northeastern.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://math.usask.ca/fvk/ruth.htm|title=The Valuation Theory Home Page: Very Sad News. Includes memorial articles from Boston Globe, Boston Herald, and Texas Star|website=math.usask.ca|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> was an American-born mathematician of German descent who lived and worked in the United States. She earned her Ph.D. in [[Mathematics]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=32774|title=Ruth Michler - The Mathematics Genealogy Project|website=genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> and she was a tenured associate professor at the [[University of North Texas]]. She died at the age of 33 while visiting [[Northeastern University]], after which at least three memorial conferences were held in her honor, and the [[Ruth I. Michler Memorial Prize]] was established in her memory.\n\n== Early years ==\nMichler was the daughter of German mathematician {{ill|Gerhard O. Michler|de}} and was born in [[Ithaca, New York]] while her family was visiting [[Cornell University]] from Germany.<ref name=\":0\" /> She grew up in Germany, living in [[T\u00fcbingen]], [[Giessen]], and [[Essen]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She completed her undergraduate studies in 1988 at the [[University of Oxford]], graduating ''summa cum laude''.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Doctoral studies and research ==\nMichler earned her Ph.D. in Mathematics in 1993 from the University of California, Berkeley. Her dissertation is titled \"Hodge components of cyclic homology of affine hypersurfaces.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Reviews review for 'Hodge-components of cyclic homology of singular affine hypersurfaces.'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 2690218}}</ref> Her advisors were [[Mariusz Wodzicki]] and [[Arthur Ogus]]. She spent the academic year 1993-1994 as a postdoc at [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] working with Leslie Roberts. In 1994, she joined the tenure-track faculty at the University of North Texas where she earned tenure in 2000. She was the author of eleven (11) research articles in [[commutative algebra]] and [[algebraic geometry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet/MRAuthorID/359582|title=Math Reviews author page: Michler, Ruth|website=mathscinet.ams.org|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.northeastern.edu/iarrobino/~michler/RMRecentPapers|title=Dr. Ruth Michler: Recent Publications|website=web.northeastern.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> She organized several special sessions at meetings of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jointmathematicsmeetings.org/meetings/national/jmm/2026_program_sss.html#title|title=American Mathematical Society meeting special session Washington, DC|website=jointmathematicsmeetings.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jointmathematicsmeetings.org/meetings/national/jmm/2031_program_ssx.html#title|title=American Mathematical Society meeting special session San Antonio|website=jointmathematicsmeetings.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ams.org/home/page/|title=American Mathematical Society meeting special session San Francisco|website=www.ams.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> The session in San Antonio resulted in a conference proceedings which Michler co-edited.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review: edited volume, 'Singularities in algebraic and analytic geometry'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 1792143}}</ref> In 2000 she was awarded a [[National Science Foundation]] POWRE grant to visit Northeastern University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0075057&HistoricalAwards=false|title=NSF Award Search: Award#0075057 - POWRE: Differentials, Singularities and Applications|website=www.nsf.gov|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\n== Memorial conferences and prize ==\nMichler was killed in an accident in Boston on November 1, 2000, when she was struck by a construction vehicle while riding her bicycle.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mathserver.neu.edu/~iarrobino/mathindex.html|title=Northeastern University, Department of Mathematics 'Tragic Accident'|website=mathserver.neu.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drivehq.com/folder/p8755087/1748796012.aspx|title=Association for Women in Mathematics Newsletter Jan-Feb 2001, In Memoriam|website=www.drivehq.com|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> Several conferences were organized in her honor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.northeastern.edu/iarrobino/~michler/RMCommemConf|title=Conferences Commemorating Dr. Ruth Michler|website=web.northeastern.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awm-math.org/meetings/awm-jmm/awm-at-jmm-2011/|title=AWM at JMM 2011|website=Association for Women in Mathematics (AWM)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> Two conferences resulted in a volume of papers dedicated to her memory<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review 'Topics in algebraic and noncommutative geometry'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 2017395}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bookstore.ams.org/conm-324/|title=Topics in Algebraic and Noncommutative Geometry: Proceedings in Memory of Ruth Michler|website=bookstore.ams.org|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> which includes a dedicatory article<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review 'Dedication [to Dr. Ruth Ingrid Michler]'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 2017396}}</ref> and an article describing her research.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review 'Dr. Ruth I. Michler's research'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 1986110}}</ref> In 2007 the [[Association for Women in Mathematics]] inaugurated the [[Ruth I. Michler Memorial Prize]] which is \"awarded annually to a woman recently promoted to Associate Professor or an equivalent position in the mathematical sciences\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awm-math.org/awards/ruth-i-michler-prize/|title=Ruth I. Michler Prize|website=Association for Women in Mathematics (AWM)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Michler, Ruth I.}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Texas faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Ithaca, New York]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Cycling road incident deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American mathematician}}\n{{infobox scientist\n  | name        = Ruth I. Michler\n  | image       = \n  | birth_date  =  March 8, 1967\n  | birth_place = [[Ithaca, New York]]\n  | death_date = November 1, 2000\n  | nationality       = American\n  | fields            = [[commutative algebra]], [[algebraic geometry]]\n  | workplaces        = [[University of North Texas]]\n  | alma_mater  = [[University of California, Berkeley]]\n  | doctoral_advisor  = [[Arthur Ogus]], [[Mariusz Wodzicki]]\n  | known_for   = \n}}\n\n'''Ruth I. Michler''' (March 8, 1967 to November 1, 2000)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Michler.html|title=Ruth Michler biography|website=www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://pi.math.cornell.edu/News/2006-2007/michler_dedication.html|title=Cornell Math - About Ruth Michler|website=pi.math.cornell.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.northeastern.edu/iarrobino/~michler/Commem|title=Commemorating Dr. Ruth Michler|website=web.northeastern.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://math.usask.ca/fvk/ruth.htm|title=The Valuation Theory Home Page: Very Sad News. Includes memorial articles from Boston Globe, Boston Herald, and Texas Star|website=math.usask.ca|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> was an American-born mathematician of German descent who lived and worked in the United States. She earned her Ph.D. in [[Mathematics]] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]],<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu/id.php?id=32774|title=Ruth Michler - The Mathematics Genealogy Project|website=genealogy.math.ndsu.nodak.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> and she was a tenured associate professor at the [[University of North Texas]]. She died at the age of 33 while visiting [[Northeastern University]], after which at least three memorial conferences were held in her honor, and the [[Ruth I. Michler Memorial Prize]] was established in her memory.\n\n== Early years ==\nMichler was the daughter of German mathematician {{ill|Gerhard O. Michler|de}} and was born in [[Ithaca, New York]] while her family was visiting [[Cornell University]] from Germany.<ref name=\":0\" /> She grew up in Germany, living in [[T\u00fcbingen]], [[Giessen]], and [[Essen]].<ref name=\":1\" /> She completed her undergraduate studies in 1988 at the [[University of Oxford]], graduating ''summa cum laude''.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Doctoral studies and research ==\nMichler earned her Ph.D. in Mathematics in 1993 from the University of California, Berkeley. Her dissertation is titled \"Hodge components of cyclic homology of affine hypersurfaces.\"<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Reviews review for 'Hodge-components of cyclic homology of singular affine hypersurfaces.'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 2690218}}</ref> Her advisors were [[Mariusz Wodzicki]] and [[Arthur Ogus]]. She spent the academic year 1993-1994 as a postdoc at [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] working with Leslie Roberts. In 1994 she joined the tenure-track faculty at the University of North Texas where she earned tenure in 2000. She was the author of eleven (11) research articles in [[commutative algebra]] and [[algebraic geometry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet/MRAuthorID/359582|title=Math Reviews author page: Michler, Ruth|website=mathscinet.ams.org|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.northeastern.edu/iarrobino/~michler/RMRecentPapers|title=Dr. Ruth Michler: Recent Publications|website=web.northeastern.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> She organized several special sessions at meetings of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jointmathematicsmeetings.org/meetings/national/jmm/2026_program_sss.html#title|title=American Mathematical Society meeting special session Washington, DC|website=jointmathematicsmeetings.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jointmathematicsmeetings.org/meetings/national/jmm/2031_program_ssx.html#title|title=American Mathematical Society meeting special session San Antonio|website=jointmathematicsmeetings.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ams.org/home/page/|title=American Mathematical Society meeting special session San Francisco|website=www.ams.org|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> The session in San Antonio resulted in a conference proceedings which Michler co-edited.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review: edited volume, 'Singularities in algebraic and analytic geometry'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 1792143}}</ref> In 2000 she was awarded a [[National Science Foundation]] POWRE grant to visit Northeastern University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/awardsearch/showAward?AWD_ID=0075057&HistoricalAwards=false|title=NSF Award Search: Award#0075057 - POWRE: Differentials, Singularities and Applications|website=www.nsf.gov|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> \n\n== Memorial conferences and prize ==\nMichler was killed in an accident in Boston on November 1, 2000, when she was struck by a construction vehicle while riding her bicycle.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mathserver.neu.edu/~iarrobino/mathindex.html|title=Northeastern University, Department of Mathematics 'Tragic Accident'|website=mathserver.neu.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.drivehq.com/folder/p8755087/1748796012.aspx|title=Association for Women in Mathematics Newsletter Jan-Feb 2001, In Memoriam|website=www.drivehq.com|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> Several conferences were organized in her honor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.northeastern.edu/iarrobino/~michler/RMCommemConf|title=Conferences Commemorating Dr. Ruth Michler|website=web.northeastern.edu|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awm-math.org/meetings/awm-jmm/awm-at-jmm-2011/|title=AWM at JMM 2011|website=Association for Women in Mathematics (AWM)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> Two conferences resulted in a volume of papers dedicated to her memory<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review 'Topics in algebraic and noncommutative geometry'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 2017395}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bookstore.ams.org/conm-324/|title=Topics in Algebraic and Noncommutative Geometry: Proceedings in Memory of Ruth Michler|website=bookstore.ams.org|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> which includes a dedicatory article<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review 'Dedication [to Dr. Ruth Ingrid Michler]'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 2017396}}</ref> and an article describing her research.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Math Review 'Dr. Ruth I. Michler's research'|last=|first=|date=|mr = 1986110}}</ref> In 2007 the [[Association for Women in Mathematics]] inaugurated the [[Ruth I. Michler Memorial Prize]] which is \"awarded annually to a woman recently promoted to Associate Professor or an equivalent position in the mathematical sciences\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awm-math.org/awards/ruth-i-michler-prize/|title=Ruth I. Michler Prize|website=Association for Women in Mathematics (AWM)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Michler, Ruth I.}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Texas faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Ithaca, New York]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Cycling road incident deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Elanecadence", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDoctoral studies and research", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth_I._Michler"}
